rine|Type VIIC]] [[submarine]] struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Baltic Sea]] near [[Hel, Poland|Hela]] ({{coord|54|25|N|18|50|E}}) with the loss of all 50 crew.<ref name=U367>{{cite web |url= http://uboat.net/boats/u367.htm |title=U-367 |publisher=Uboat |accessdate=18 March 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{GS|UIT-6||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The submarine was sunk in an Allied air raid on Monfalcone.<ref name=seekrieg194503/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|German patrol boat|UJ-1105 Wilhelm Loh||2}} \n|flag={{navy|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The naval trawler/submarine chaser was bombed and sunk by Allied aircraft in the [[Skagerrak]].<ref>{{csr|register=MSI|id=5614856|shipname=Uj.1105 |accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref> }}\n{{shipwreck list end}}\n\n==17 March==\n{{shipwreck list begin |date=17 March 1945 |sort=}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMS|Daffodil||2}} \n|flag={{navy|UK}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The Landing Craft carrier hit a mine off [[Dieppe]] and sank the next morning. Nine crew were killed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.grieme.org/d-3/daffodil-2.html#histoire |title=Daffodil |publisher=www.grieme.org |accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship=''Ellringon'' (or&nbsp;''Ellrington'')\n|flag={{flag|United States|1912}}\n|desc=The 22-[[gross register ton]], {{convert|47.6|ft|m|1|adj=on}} [[fishing vessel]] was destroyed by fire at [[Cordova, Alaska|Cordova]], [[Territory of Alaska]].<ref name=alaskashipwreckse>[https://alaskashipwreck.com/shipwrecks-a-z/alaska-shipwrecks-e/ alaskashipwreck.com Alaska Shipwrecks (E)]</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{HMCS|Guysborough|J52|6}} \n|flag={{navy|Canada|1911}}\n|desc=[[World War II]]: The {{sclass-|Bangor|minesweeper}} was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Bay of Biscay]] by the [[submarine]] {{GS|U-868||2}} ({{navy|Nazi Germany}}) with the loss of 51 of her crew. About 40 survivors were rescued by the [[frigate]] {{HMS|Inglis|K570|6}} ({{navy|UK}}).\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese cargo ship|Ikomasan Maru||2}} \n|flag={{nowrap begin}}{{navy|Empire of Japan}}{{nowrap end}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was damaged in the [[South China Sea]] off [[Fuchow, China|Fuchow]], [[China]], by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Spot|SS-413|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}) and was beached on [[Matsu Island, China|Matsu]] ({{coord|25|58|N|119|58|E}}) off the coast of China. Seven passengers, four gunners, and six crew were lost. Later in the day she was bombed by [[United States Army Air Forces]] [[North American B-25 Mitchell]] aircraft, killing another five crewmen. The beached ship was bombed again on 26 March by U.S. Army Air Forces [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]] aircraft and destroyed.<ref name=\"http\">{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/CD-41_t.htm |title=Japanese Escorts |publisher=Combinedfleet.com |accessdate=17 March 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Iris|1921|2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was bombed and sunk at [[\u00c5lesund]], [[Norway]] by [[de Havilland Mosquito]] aircraft of [[No. 143 Squadron RAF|143]], [[No. 235 Squadron RAF|235]], [[No. 248 Squadron RAF|248]], and [[No. 333 Squadron RAF|333]] Squadrons, [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194503/><ref name=NorH2>{{cite web|url= http://www.warsailors.com/freefleet/norfleeth2.html |title= Norwegian Merchant Fleet 1939 - 1945, Ships beginning with He |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=HomeL>{{cite web |url=http://www.warsailors.com/homefleet/shipsl.html |title=Norwegian Homefleet - WW II, Ships starting with L |publisher=Warsailors |accessdate=9 February 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Log||2}} \n|flag={{flag|Norway}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was bombed and sunk at [[\u00c5lesund]], [[Norway]], by [[de Havilland Mosquito]] aircraft of [[No. 143 Squadron RAF|143]], [[No. 235 Squadron RAF|235]], [[No. 248 Squadron RAF|248]], and [[No. 333 Squadron RAF|333]] Squadrons, [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194503/><ref name=HomeL/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Margarethe Cords||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was [[torpedo]]ed and sunk in the [[Baltic Se]]a, south of [[Bornholm]], [[Denmark]] ({{coord|54|48|N|15|00|E}}), by the [[submarine]] {{ship|Soviet submarine|K-53||2}} ({{navy|Soviet Union|1935}}) with the loss of two lives.<ref name=seekrieg194503/><ref>{{csr |register=MSI |id=5606692 |shipname=Margarethe Cords |accessdate=27 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forum-marinearchiv.de/smf/index.php?topic=13445.0 |title=Margarethe Cords |publisher=www.forum-marinearchiv.de |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{ship|Japanese cargo ship|Nanking Maru||2}} \n|flag={{nowrap begin}}{{army|Empire of Japan}}{{nowrap end}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was sunk in the [[South China Sea]] off [[Fuchow, China|Fuchow]] ({{coord|25|33|N|120|10|E}}), [[China]], by the [[submarine]] {{USS|Spot|SS-413|6}} ({{navy|USA|1912}}). Of the 503 on board \u2013 411 passengers, 32 gunners, and 60 crew \u2013 502 were lost.<ref name=\"http\"/>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Remagen||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] was bombed and sunk off [[\u00c5lesund]], [[Norway]], by [[de Havilland Mosquito]] aircraft of [[No. 143 Squadron RAF|143]], [[No. 235 Squadron RAF|235]], [[No. 248 Squadron RAF|248]], and [[No. 333 Squadron RAF|333]] Squadrons, [[Royal Air Force]].<ref name=seekrieg194503/><ref>{{csr |register=MSI |id=3007411 |shipname=Rimage |accessdate=15 April 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n{{shipwreck list item\n|ship={{SS|Rixh\u00f6ft||2}} \n|flag={{flagcountry|Nazi Germany}}\n|desc=World War II: The [[cargo ship]] struck a [[naval mine|mine]] and sank in the [[Baltic Sea]] off [[Warnem\u