ctions:'''\n*{{\u2022}}[[Liberal conservatism]]<ref name=Bale>{{cite journal|authors=Tim Bale, Se\u00e1n Hanley, and Aleks Szczerbiak|title='May Contain Nuts'? The Reality behind the Rhetoric Surrounding the British Conservatives' New Group in the European Parliament|pages=85\u201398|volume=81|issue=1|date=March 2010|journal=The Political Quarterly|doi=10.1111/j.1467-923X.2009.02067.x|quote=when taken together they form not so much a coherent whole as a mix of liberal conservatives (the Conservatives, ODS, LDD and MDF) and conservative nationalists (PiS and TB-LNNK).}}</ref>\n*{{\u2022}}[[Economic liberalism]]\n*{{\u2022}}[[Nationalism]]<ref name=Bale/>\n*{{\u2022}}[[Right-wing populism]]}}\n|position     = [[Right-wing politics|Right-wing]]<ref name=\"Toemmel2014\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jul/15/ursula-von-der-leyen-makes-final-pledges-secure-eu-top-job|title=Ursula von der Leyen makes final pledges to secure EU's top job|quote=Von der Leyen says in her letters that she hopes the \"snapshot\" on her positions, some of which are retreads of previous proposals from the commission, will reassure her critics, although there is a risk of putting off MEPs within the more Eurosceptic and '''rightwing European Conservatives and Reformists group''', in which Poland's Law and Justice is the largest party.|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=15 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-eu-jobs-vonderleyen-explainer/explainer-von-der-leyens-rocky-path-to-confirmation-as-eu-commission-chief-idUSKCN1U71M3|title=Explainer: Von der Leyen's rocky path to confirmation as EU Commission chief|quote=The '''right-wing European Conservatives and Reformists (ECR)''', will decide just ahead of the vote whether to support von der Leyen, but officials say the group is divided over the issue.|agency=[[Reuters]]|date=12 July 2019}}</ref><br> with [[far-right]] factions<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.europeaninterest.eu/article/dutch-greek-far-right-parties-join-ecr-group/|title=Dutch and Greek far-right parties join ECR Group|work=European Interest|date=6 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=McDonnell|first=Duncan|last2=Werner|first2=Annika|date=4 May 2018|title=Respectable radicals: why some radical right parties in the European Parliament forsake policy congruence|journal=Journal of European Public Policy|volume=25|issue=5|pages=747\u2013763|doi=10.1080/13501763.2017.1298659|issn=1350-1763}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://cadmus.eui.eu/bitstream/handle/1814/56165/RSCAS_2018_38.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y|title=Populist Radical Right Parties and EU Policies: How coherent are their claims?|page=5|first=Gerda|last=Falkner|first2=Georg |last2=Plattner|journal=EUI Working Paper RSCAS|year=2018|issue=38}}</ref> \n|europarties  = [[European Conservatives and Reformists Party]]<br>[[European Christian Political Movement]]\n|associated   = [[New Direction (think tank)|New Direction]]\n|chairs       = [[Raffaele Fitto]]<br />[[Ryszard Legutko]]\n|1blankname1  = Vice-Chairs\n|1namedata1   = {{plainlist|\n*[[Ryszard Legutko]]\n*[[Hans-Olaf Henkel]]\n*[[Raffaele Fitto]]\n*[[Roberts Zile]]\n*[[Helga Stevens]]\n*[[Geoffrey Van Orden]]}}\n|meps         = {{Composition bar|61|705|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|website      = {{URL|www.ecrgroup.eu}}\n}}\n\nThe '''European Conservatives and Reformists''' ('''ECR''')<ref name=\"SCR16665126\"/> is a [[Euroscepticism|Eurosceptic]],<ref name=\"Gillissen2010\">{{cite book|author=Christophe Gillissen|title=Ireland: Looking East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QoKaFhA-unwC&pg=PA157|year=2010|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-90-5201-652-8|page=157}}</ref><ref name=\"Holm-Hansen\">{{cite book|author=J\u00f8rn Holm-Hansen|editor1=Ingo Peters|editor2= Elisabeth Bakke|chapter=Continuity and Change in Polish Party Politics Since 1989|title=20 Years Since the Fall of the Berlin Wall: Transitions, State Break-Up and Democratic Politics in Central Europe and Germany|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L3LsDJWq7DAC&pg=PA277|accessdate=6 February 2013|year=2011|publisher=BWV Verlag|isbn=978-3-8305-1975-1|page=277}}</ref><ref name=\"Aydin-D\u00fczgit2012\">{{cite book|author=Senem Aydin-D\u00fczgit|title=Constructions of European Identity: Debates and Discourses on Turkey and the EU|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DTviXmK9zgkC&pg=PA16|year=2012|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-28351-1|page=16}}</ref><ref name=\"Slomp2011\">{{cite book|author=Hans Slomp|title=Europe, A Political Profile: An American Companion to European Politics &#91;2 volumes&#93;: An American Companion to European Politics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LmfAPmwE6YYC&pg=PA245|year=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-0-313-39182-8|page=245}}</ref><ref name=\"ColeDeighan2012\">{{cite book|author1=Matt Cole|author2=Helen Deighan|title=Political Parties in Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ea1vAAAAQBAJ&pg=PT39|year=2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-7486-6903-5|page=39}}</ref> anti-[[Federal Europe|federalist]]<ref name=\"Foget\"/><ref name=\"Gillissen2010\"/><ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|date = 22 June 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8112581.stm|title = Conservative MEPs form new group|publisher = BBC |accessdate = 22 June 2009}}</ref> [[political group of the European Parliament]]. The ECR is the parliamentary group of the [[European Conservatives and Reformists Party]] (ECR Party) [[European political party]] (formerly known as the ''Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe'' (2016\u20132019) or ''Alliance of European Conservatives and Reformists'' (2009\u20132016)), but also includes [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s from four other European parties and thirteen MEPs without European party affiliation. The group focuses on reforming the [[European Union]] (EU) on the basis of Eurorealism<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ecrgroup.eu/about-us/our-history/|title=ECR Group \u2013 European Conservatives and Reformists Group|first=European Conservatives and|last=Reformists|website=ecrgroup.eu|access-date=15 December 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180219204118/http://ecrgroup.eu/about-us/our-history/|archive-date=19 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> as opposed to total rejection of the EU (anti-EU-ism).<ref>{{cite book|author=Erkanor Saka|title=Mediating the EU: Deciphering the Transformation of Turkish Elites (PhD Thesis)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Hy77juW0DNQC&pg=PA202|accessdate=9 March 2016|year=2009|isbn=978-1-109-21663-9|page=202}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Matthew|title=Why anti-EUism is not left-wing|url=http://www.workersliberty.org/story/2011/10/26/why-anti-euism-not-left-wing|website=Workers' Liberty|publisher=[[Alliance for Workers Liberty]]|accessdate=31 January 2016|date=26 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe ECR was founded around the [[Movement for European Reform]] after the [[2009 European Parliament election|2009 European elections]] at the behest of [[Conservative Party (UK)|British Conservative Party]] leader [[David Cameron]]. Currently it is the sixth-largest group in the European Parliament with 61 MEPs from 15 countries.\n\nThe group is considered right-wing.<ref name=\"Toemmel2014\">{{bulleted list\n| {{cite book|author=Ingeborg Toemmel|title=The European Union: What it is and how it Works|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rkGVBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA158|year=2014|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-42754-0|page=158}}\n| {{cite news |url=http://euobserver.com/843/28350 |title=EU parliament sees birth of new right-wing group |newspaper=[[EUobserver]] |date=22 June 2009 |accessdate=18 July 2011}}\n| {{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6908148.ece |title=Tory minders gag right-wing allies in the ECR |newspaper=The Times |date=8 November 2009 |accessdate=18 July 2011 |location=London}}\n| {{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8235478.stm |title=New-look European Parliament  |publisher=BBC News |date=3 September 2009 |accessdate=18 July 2011}}}}</ref> The largest party in the group by number of MEPs is the [[Law and Justice]] (PiS) of [[Poland]].\n\n==Founding principles and ideology==\n[[File:Vltava in Prague.jpg|right|thumb|245px|The Prague Declaration was first proposed in 2003.]]\nThe genesis of the ECR dates back to 2005, and possibly{{When|date=June 2019}} earlier.{{Citation needed|date=June 2019}} A [[political groups of the European Parliament|political group in the European Parliament]] cannot be officially recognised if it contains MEPs from only a single member state. Instead, it must meet the minimum threshold required by the European Parliament's Rules of Procedure.<ref name=\"Rule3020090701\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//TEXT+RULES-EP+20090714+RULE-030+DOC+XML+V0//EN&language=EN&navigationBar=YES|title=Rules of Procedure of the European Parliament \u2013 July 2009 \u2013 Rule 30 \u2013 Formation of political groups|publisher=European Parliament}}</ref><ref name=\"Rule2920090406\">{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?pubRef=-//EP//TEXT+RULES-EP+20090309+RULE-029+DOC+XML+V0//EN&navigationBar=YES|title=Rules of Procedure of the European Parliament \u2013 March 2009 \u2013 Rule 29 \u2013 Formation of political groups|publisher=European Parliament}}</ref> Any party seeking to create a group must therefore seek partners. The [[Technical Group of Independents (1999\u20132001)|last mixed group in the European Parliament]] was forcibly dissolved. Since then, groups have been required to demonstrate ideological coherence. This is usually done by publishing a document (sometimes called a ''constituent declaration'') stating the principles to which each group member is expected to adhere. The constituent declaration of the ECR has become known as the [[Prague Declaration of European Conservatives and Reformists|Prague Declaration]]. That document outlines the following principles:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ecrgroup.eu/?p=1100 |title=The Prague Declaration : European Conservatives and Reformists Group |publisher= Ecrgroup.eu |accessdate= 7 September 2013}}</ref>\n# Free enterprise, [[Free trade|free]] and [[fair trade]] and competition, minimal regulation, lower taxation, and [[small government]] as the ultimate catalysts for [[individualism|individual freedom]] and personal and national prosperity.\n# Freedom of the individual, more personal responsibility and greater democratic accountability.\n# [[Sustainable energy|Sustainable, clean energy]] supply with an emphasis on [[energy security]].\n# The importance of the family as the bedrock of society.\n# The [[national sovereignty|sovereign integrity]] of the [[nation state]], opposition to [[Federalisation of the European Union|EU federalism]] and a renewed respect for true [[subsidiarity]].\n# The over-riding value of the [[Atlanticism|transatlantic security relationship]] in a revitalised [[NATO]], and support for young democracies across Europe.\n# [[Border control|Effectively controlled]] [[Anti-immigration|immigration]] and an end to abuse of asylum procedures\n# Efficient and modern [[public services]] and sensitivity to the needs of both rural and urban communities.\n# An end to waste and excessive [[bureaucracy]] and a commitment to greater [[transparency (behavior)|transparency]] and probity in the EU institutions and use of EU funds.\n# Respect and equitable treatment for all EU countries, new and old, large and small.\n\nIdeologically, member parties of the ECR have traditionally sat on the centre-right<ref>{{cite news |title=Conservative MEPs form new 'anti-federalist' group in the European Parliament|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/conservative/5602509/Conservative-MEPs-form-new-anti-federalist-group-in-the-European-Parliament.html |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=22 June 2009 |accessdate=10 September 2019 |location=London}}</ref> to right-wing<ref>{{cite news |title=New-look European Parliament|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8235478.stm |publisher= BBC News |date=22 June 2009 |accessdate= 10 September 2019}}</ref> of the political spectrum with an [[economically liberal]] and anti-federalist outlook and an initial reluctance from the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] to include hard-line anti-immigration parties. However, in recent years the group has come to contain a faction of [[nationalist]] and [[right-wing populist]] movements,<ref>{{cite news |title=Dutch and Greek far-right parties join ECR Group|url=https://www.europeaninterest.eu/article/dutch-greek-far-right-parties-join-ecr-group/|work= European Interest |date=6 June 2019 |accessdate= 10 September 2019}}</ref> with some former ECR members arguing that the group has shifted considerably further to the right over time.<ref>{{cite news|work=Teller Report|title=ChristenUnie does not want Forum for Democracy: A European family quarrel|date=22 April 2019|url=https://www.tellerreport.com/news/2019-05-22---christenunie-does-not-want-forum-for-democracy--a-european-family-quarrel-.SJbMgUZmpE.html}}</ref>\n\nThe shift to the right was increased following the [[Brexit|withdrawal of the United Kingdom from the European Union]], since the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] lost its representation in the [[European Parliament]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins: 2005\u201306===\nIn 2005, the [[Conservative Party (UK)|British Conservative Party]] held a [[2005 Conservative Party leadership election|leadership contest]]. During the [[Sixth European Parliament|sixth term of the European Parliament]], Conservative Party MEPs sat in the [[European Democrats]] (ED), a subgroup of the [[European People's Party Group|European People's Party\u2013European Democrats]] (EPP-ED) group, which is dominated by the [[European People's Party]] (EPP). Leadership contender [[David Cameron]] argued for withdrawal of the Conservatives from EPP-ED and the formation of a new group. Upon taking office as Conservative leader in December 2005, Cameron indicated that the launch of a new group would be undertaken immediately.<ref name=\"Kite\"/> The motives for forming this group was the EPP-ED was too [[Federalisation of the European Union|federalist]], while the Tories opposed stronger European integration.<ref name=\":0hh\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7938482.stm|title=Tories leaving Europe's EPP group|date=11 March 2009|publisher=[[BBC News]]|access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2006, Cameron ordered [[Shadow Foreign Secretary]] [[William Hague]] to ensure the new group was created by 13 July 2006.<ref name=\"Kite\">{{cite news|author= Kite, Melissa|date = 11 June 2006|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1520953/Cameron-gives-Hague-month-to-get-MEPs-out-of-Brussels-group.html|title = Cameron gives Hague month to get MEPs out of Brussels group|work = The Daily Telegraph|accessdate = 28 September 2009 | location=London}}</ref> However, when that date arrived, it was announced that the launch of the new European Parliament group was delayed until after the 2009 elections.<ref name=\"Kubosova\">{{cite web|author= Kubosova, Lucia|date = 13 July 2006|url = http://euobserver.com/843/22085|title = Plans to form new MEP group kicked into 2009|work = [[EUobserver]]|accessdate = 26 March 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Movement for European Reform===\nIn the interim, a pan-European alliance, called the [[Movement for European Reform]] (MER), was founded and functioned outside of the European Parliament.<ref name=\"Euro declaration\">{{cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/5175994.stm|title = Cameron Euro declaration|publisher = BBC News|accessdate = 27 May 2008 | date=13 July 2006}}</ref> The same day, the [[Law and Justice]] and [[Civic Platform]] parties of Poland were identified as potential members of the new group: However, Civic Platform stated that it would not leave the EPP, and the Law and Justice stated that it planned to stay aligned to UEN.<ref name=\"Mulvey\">{{cite news|author= Mulvey, Steven|date = 13 July 2006|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/5176782.stm|title = Q & A: The Tories and the EPP|publisher = BBC News|accessdate = 27 May 2008}}</ref> The next day, [[Reg Empey|Sir Reg Empey]], the leader of the [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP), suggested that the UUP could join the new group after the 2009 election.<ref name=\"Belfast\">{{cite news|title= Could the UUP be ready to leave the European Democrats?|publisher= [[The News Letter|The Belfast News Letter]]|date= 14 July 2006}}</ref> In the event of the election, the UUP ran under the banner of the [[Ulster Conservatives and Unionists]], an [[electoral alliance]] between the Conservative Party and the Ulster Unionists.\n\n[[File:Mirek Topolanek.jpg|thumb|180px|right|[[Mirek Topol\u00e1nek]]]] The Czech [[Civic Democratic Party (Czech Republic)|Civic Democratic Party]] (ODS) was part of MER but its leader, [[Mirek Topol\u00e1nek]], did not rule out staying in EPP-ED.<ref name=\"EUobserver EPP\">{{cite web|year = 2007|url = http://euobserver.com/9/23639|title = Will Mirek really leave the EPP-ED?|work = [[EUobserver]]|accessdate = 28 May 2008}}</ref> Topol\u00e1nek then attended the EPP Summit (a meeting of heads of state and government of the [[European People's Party]]) of 21 June 2007, adding speculation about the fragility of the new group.<ref name=\"EPP summit\">{{cite web|year = 2007|url = http://www.epp.eu/newsdetail.php?hoofdmenuID=4&newsID=259&submenuID=49&subsubmenuID=139|title = 16 Heads of State meet at an EPP summit|publisher = [[European People's Party]]|accessdate = 28 May 2008|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080411022148/http://www.epp.eu/newsdetail.php?hoofdmenuID=4&newsID=259&submenuID=49&subsubmenuID=139|archive-date = 11 April 2008|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nLater in 2007, the relations between the EPP and the Conservative Party further deteriorated when the EPP voiced its opposition to the UK holding a referendum of the [[Treaty of Lisbon]], something the Tories had campaigned for.<ref name=\":0hh\"/>\n\nIn July 2008, the European Parliament raised the 2009 threshold for forming a group to 25 members and representing 7 member states.<ref name=\"threshold increase\">{{cite web|year = 2008|url = http://www.europarl.europa.eu/sides/getDoc.do?language=en&reference=20080708IPR33697| title = European Parliament increases threshold to form a political group|publisher = [[European Parliament]]|accessdate = 24 August 2008}}</ref> Topol\u00e1nek, after being re-elected Leader of the ODS on 7 December 2008, attended yet another EPP Summit, on 11 December 2008.<ref name=\"new EPP Summit\">{{cite web|year = 2008|url = http://www.epp.eu/newsdetail.php?hoofdmenuID=4&newsID=466&submenuID=49&subsubmenuID=147|title = EPP calls on the EU for a solution for ratification of the Lisbon Treaty|publisher = [[European People's Party]]|accessdate = 12 December 2008}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===2009 European Parliament elections===\nAs the [[2009 European Parliament election|2009 European elections]] approached, Cameron, Topol\u00e1nek, and Conservative MEP [[Geoffrey Van Orden]] (a 'point-man' for the new group)<ref name=\"Novinite April\"/> were looking for partners. The list of possible partners was kept secret.<ref name=\"Economist\">{{cite news|date = 26 March 2009|url = http://www.economist.com/node/13362051|title=Those exceptional British|work = The Economist|accessdate = 26 March 2009}}</ref>\n\nPeople or parties that were rumoured to be possible partners in the new group included [[Law and Justice]];<ref name=\"Taylor\"/><ref name=\"Moszynski\">{{cite web|year = 2009|url = http://www.rfi.fr/actufr/articles/111/article_79181.asp|title = La rupture conservatrice|author = Moszynski, Piotr|publisher = [[Radio France International]]|accessdate = 11 March 2009|language = French}}</ref><ref name=\"Smyth\"/> [[Lega Nord]];<ref name=\"Taylor\"/><ref name=\"TOL6515060\"/> the [[Danish People's Party]];<ref name=\"Taylor\"/><ref name=\"TOL6515060\"/> [[For Fatherland and Freedom/LNNK|For Fatherland and Freedom]],<ref name=\"Economist\"/><ref name=\"Taylor\"/> [[Order and Justice]],<ref name=\"Taylor\"/> the [[Pensioners' Party (Italy)|Pensioners' Party]];<ref name=\"Mardell\">{{cite web|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/thereporters/markmardell/2009/03/tories_look_for_new_partners.html|title=Tories look for new partners|date=24 March 2009|author = Mardell, Mark|publisher = BBC News|accessdate = 24 March 2009|author-link=Mark Mardell}}</ref> [[Order, Law and Justice]];<ref name=\"Novinite April\">{{cite web|date = 5 April 2009|url = http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=102523|title = EU Conservatives Stand Firm behind Bulgaria's Order, Law and Justice Party|publisher = [[Novinite]]|accessdate = 24 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Novinite March\">{{cite web|date = 27 March 2009|url = http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=102286|title = UK Conservative Party Leader Cameron Welcomes Bulgaria Opposition MP Yanev|publisher = [[Novinite]]|accessdate = 24 April 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"HixBulgaria\">{{cite web|date=23 April 2009 |author=Hix, Simon, Michael Marsh and Nick Vivyan |url=http://www.predict09.eu/default/en-us/state_analyses.aspx#bulgaria |title=Predict 09 \u2013 Analysis by Member State \u2013 Bulgaria |publisher=[[Burson-Marsteller]] |accessdate=24 April 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090410052202/http://www.predict09.eu/default/en-us/state_analyses.aspx |archivedate=10 April 2009 }}</ref> [[Libertas.eu|Libertas]];<ref>{{cite web|date = 3 June 2009|url = http://www.euractiv.com/eu-elections/new-conservative-group-rock-parliament/article-182782|title = New conservative group to rock next Parliament|publisher = EurActiv.com|accessdate = 3 June 2009}}</ref> [[Civic Union (Latvia)|Civic Union]];<ref name=\"The Guardian\">{{cite news|date = 9 June 2009|author = Traynor, Ian|url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jun/08/conservative-alliance-european-union|title =David Cameron on track to form alliance of Eurosceptics|work = The Guardian|accessdate = 9 June 2009 | location=London}}</ref> [[Electoral Action of Poles in Lithuania]],<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/> [[ChristianUnion \u2013 Reformed Political Party|ChristianUnion-SGP]];<ref>{{cite web|date = 8 June 2009|url = http://www.dutchnews.nl/news/archives/2009/06/eu_vote_cusgp_may_link_to_cons.php|title =EU vote: CU/SGP may link to Conservatives|publisher = DutchNews.nl|accessdate = 10 June 2009}}</ref> the independent [[Indrek Tarand]];<ref name=\"The Guardian\"/> and [[List Dedecker|Lijst Dedecker]]'s [[Derk Jan Eppink]];<ref name=\"Taylor\"/><ref name=\"Moszynski\"/> from member states such as the Czech Republic,<ref name=\"Grossman\">{{cite news|author= Grossman, David|date = 10 March 2009|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/7935355.stm|title = The Tories' European dilemma|publisher = [[BBC]]|accessdate = 11 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"Banks\"/> Poland,<ref name=\"Grossman\"/><ref name=\"Banks\"/> Italy,<ref name=\"Grossman\"/> Sweden,<ref name=\"Grossman\"/> the [[Baltic states|Baltic]] and [[Balkan states]],<ref name=\"Grossman\"/> [[Belgium]],<ref name=\"Banks\"/> and the [[Netherlands]].<ref name=\"Banks\"/> Speculation also considered the remnants of the [[Union for Europe of the Nations]] (UEN) group, which was thought to be on the verge of collapse{{according to whom|date=January 2015}} after the decision of [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] to join the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Group|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] (ALDE)<ref name=\"Connolly\">{{cite web|date = 15 March 2009|url = http://www.sbpost.ie/post/pages/p/story.aspx-qqqt=NEWS+FEATURES-qqqm=nav-qqqid=40257-qqqx=1.asp|title = FF to join liberal Euro group next month |work = [[The Sunday Business Post]]|author=Connolly, Niamh|accessdate = 26 March 2009}}</ref> and the Italian [[National Alliance (Italy)|National Alliance]] merging with EPP member party [[Forza Italia]]. Lajos Bokros, elected on the list of the [[Hungarian Democratic Forum]] (MDF) joined the group as the EPP did not want to accept him on pressure of the rival [[Fidesz]].\n\nThe new group was provisionally named the European Conservatives,<ref name=\"Smyth\">{{cite news|url = https://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2009/0313/1224242799550.html|title=Tories to set up new parliamentary group|date=13 March 2009|author = Smyth, Jamie|work = [[The Irish Times]]|accessdate = 26 March 2009}}</ref> (echoing the [[European Conservatives|1970s group of the same name]]), which was then changed to European Conservatives and Reformists.<ref>{{cite news|date = 15 May 2009|author = Charter, David|url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6289822.ece|title = David Cameron's new European allies set to include odd bedfellows|work = The Times|accessdate = 15 May 2009 | location=London}}</ref> The original estimates were firmed up to 84 MEPs,<ref name=\"Taylor\">{{cite web|date = 12 March 2009|url = http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/uk-conservatives-to-leave-the-epp-ed-group/64257.aspx|title = UK Conservatives to leave the EPP-ED group|author = Taylor, Simon|publisher = [[European Voice]]|accessdate = 11 March 2009}}</ref> then to approximately 60.<ref name=\"Banks\">{{cite web|date = 25 March 2009|url = http://www.theparliament.com/policy-focus/justice/justice-article/newsarticle/uk-tories-well-on-track-to-forming-new-eu-grouping/|title = UK Tories 'well on track' to forming new EU grouping|publisher = Theparliament.com|author=Banks, Martin|accessdate = 26 March 2009}}</ref> Frictions surfaced, as the ODS wanted the new group to have as many MEPs as possible, whilst the Conservatives wanted to disbar anti-immigrant parties in the new group, including the Danish People's Party and Lega Nord.<ref name=\"TOL6515060\">{{cite news|date = 17 June 2009|url = http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article6515060.ece|title =Tory party upsets Czech partners with choice of anti-federalist MEPs|work = The Times|accessdate = 22 June 2009 | location=London | first1=David | last1=Charter}}</ref>\n\n===Formation===\nOn 22 June 2009, the first official list of the new group's members was released.<ref name=\"BBC\"/> On 24 June, the group held its inaugural meeting, in which Conservative MEP [[Timothy Kirkhope]] was named interim leader.<ref name=DTelArticle25June09>{{cite news|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/eu/5626057/Tory-MEP-voices-real-concern-over-new-European-grouping.html|title=Tory MEP voices 'real concern' over new European grouping |date=25 March 2009|author = Banks, Martin|work = The Daily Telegraph|accessdate = 22 July 2009 | location=London}}</ref> [[Adam Bielan]] of PiS and [[Jan Zahradil]] of the ODS were named interim vice-chairmen.\n\nAt the first sitting of the [[7th European Parliament|Seventh European Parliament]], on 14 July 2009, outgoing Parliament President [[Hans-Gert P\u00f6ttering]] announced that applications from all new and returning groups had been received and approved, including ECR. The group then became eligible for EU funding, office space, and committee places.\n\n[[File:Michal Kaminski 2007 10.jpg|thumb|left|Former ECR chairman, [[Micha\u0142 Kami\u0144ski]]]]\nThe first election for the group leadership was also scheduled for 14 July 2009, pitting interim leader Kirkhope against fellow Briton [[Geoffrey Van Orden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theparliament.com/no_cache/latestnews/news-article/newsarticle/british-tories-fight-it-out-for-leadership-of-new-eurosceptic-group/ |title=British Tories fight it out for leadership of new Eurosceptic group |date=9 July 2009 |author=Banks, Martin |publisher=Theparliament.com |accessdate=10 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090724154635/http://www.theparliament.com/no_cache/latestnews/news-article/newsarticle/british-tories-fight-it-out-for-leadership-of-new-eurosceptic-group/ |archivedate=24 July 2009 }}</ref> However, both Conservative leadership candidates were forced to forfeit the leadership to prevent it from falling apart, when Conservative MEP [[Edward McMillan-Scott]] defied his party whip and stood for one of the vice-presidency posts despite pledges the previous week that Polish MEP [[Micha\u0142 Kami\u0144ski]] would be backed for it. Kami\u0144ski's bid for [[Vice-President of the European Parliament]] subsequently failed, and the Polish MEPs threatened to abandon the new caucus unless Kami\u0144ski was made the group leader in the parliament.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ian Traynor in Strasbourg |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jul/15/conservatives-eu-parliament-eurosceptic-group-leadership |title=Tories give up EU parliamentary leadership of Eurosceptic group &#124; Politics |work=The Guardian |date= 15 July 2009|accessdate=27 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref> Kirkhope went to an emergency meeting with Polish MEPs in [[Strasbourg]] and proposed sharing the group leadership with the Kami\u0144ski; however, this was not accepted, and he had to step down as coalition leader, withdrawing in favour of Kami\u0144ski. McMillan-Scott, who alleged that the Conservative's new allies in Poland are 'racist and homophobic', had the Conservative [[whip (politics)|whip]] withdrawn in the European Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.newstatesman.com/2009/07/mcmillan-scott-european-mep|title=Conservatives expel MEP after row over right-wing bloc|date=15 July 2009|work = New Statesman|accessdate = 15 July 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theparliament.com/no_cache/latestnews/news-article/newsarticle/suspended-tory-mep-hits-back-at-allegations-of-disloyalty/ |title=McMillan-Scott hits back at allegations of disloyalty |date=15 July 2009 |publisher=Theparliament.com |accessdate=16 July 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722173329/http://www.theparliament.com/no_cache/latestnews/news-article/newsarticle/suspended-tory-mep-hits-back-at-allegations-of-disloyalty/ |archivedate=22 July 2009 }}</ref> In March 2010, McMillan-Scott joined the British [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] and the ALDE group.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/8564914.stm |title=Ex-Tory MEP Edward McMillan-Scott joins Lib Dems |publisher=BBC News |date=12 March 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Leadership changes and upheavals in membership===\nGroup chairman Kami\u0144ski left [[Law and Justice]] (PiS) in November 2010, saying that the party had been taken over by the far-right. Kami\u0144ski and other Law and Justice MPs and MEPs formed a new Polish party, [[Poland Comes First]], formed as a breakaway from Law and Justice following dissatisfaction with the direction and leadership of [[Jaros\u0142aw Kaczy\u0144ski]]. Kami\u0144ski initially remained of the group, but other Law and Justice MEPs argued he should step down.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/nov/22/conservatives-eu-alliance-michal-kaminski Conservatives' EU alliance in turmoil as Micha\u0142 Kami\u0144ski leaves 'far right' party], ''The Guardian'', 22 November 2010</ref> On 15 December, rumours emerged that the eleven remaining PiS MEPs might leave the ECR and join the right-wing [[Europe of Freedom and Democracy]] (EFD) group instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theparliament.com/latest-news/article/newsarticle/future-of-eu-parliament-group-under-renewed-pressure/ |title=Future of EU parliament group under renewed pressure |publisher= Theparliament.com |date=15 December 2010 |accessdate= 7 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, Kami\u0144ski announced he would resign his chairmanship, effective 8 March, when a replacement would be elected. Former interim leader [[Timothy Kirkhope]] was said to be the front runner,<ref>{{cite news |title=Conservative confusion |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/conservative-confusion-/70147.aspx  |newspaper=[[European Voice]] |date=3 February 2011 |accessdate=10 February 2011}}</ref> but lost the election to [[Jan Zahradil]] of the [[Czech Republic]]'s ODS.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/2011/march/czech-beats-british-conservative-to-lead-ep-group/70478.aspx |title=Czech beats British Conservative to lead EP group |last=Taylor |first=Simon |publisher=European Voice |date=8 March 2011}}</ref> Zahradil has been in talks with other parties about joining the ECR.<ref>{{cite news |title=ECR has moved from squabbling to stability |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/-ecr-has-moved-from-squabbling-to-stability-/70752.aspx |newspaper=[[European Voice]] |date=7 April 2011 |accessdate=23 May 2011}}</ref> In late March, David Cameron invited the [[New Flemish Alliance]] (N-VA) to join the group.<ref>{{cite news |title=When Dave met Bart |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/when-dave-met-bart/70645.aspx |newspaper=[[European Voice]] |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=23 May 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe May 2011 resignation of [[Silvana Koch-Mehrin]], one of the fourteen [[Vice President of the European Parliament|Vice-Presidents of the European Parliament]], led to the ECR considering putting another candidate forward to take the position they were denied through McMillan-Scott's defection.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/jostling-for-position/71131.aspx |title=Jostling for position |publisher=European Voice |date=19 May 2011}}</ref> Conservative Party MEP [[Giles Chichester]] was nominated on 31 May, and was elected unopposed by the Parliament on 5 July 2011,<ref>{{cite news |title=Chichester and Podimata appointed vice-presidents |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/chichester-and-podimata-appointed-vice-presidents/71552.aspx |newspaper=[[European Voice]] |date=7 July 2011 |accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref> after the ALDE group to which Koch-Mehrin belongs failed to find a willing and suitable candidate.<ref>{{cite news |title=Just the job for a liberal? |url=http://www.europeanvoice.com/article/imported/just-the-job-for-a-liberal-/71320.aspx |newspaper=[[European Voice]] |date=9 June 2011 |accessdate=15 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 December 2011, a new leadership was elected, with [[Martin Callanan]] as chairman and [[Jan Zahradil]], [[Geoffrey Van Orden]], [[Ryszard Legutko]], and [[Derk Jan Eppink]] as Vice-Chairmen. On 26 December 2011, four members of [[United Poland]] \u2013 who had split from Law and Justice in November \u2013 left the ECR to join the [[Europe of Freedom and Democracy]] (EFD) group. On 17 January 2012, Czech [[Old\u0159ich Vlas\u00e1k]] replaced Chichester as the ECR's Vice-President of the Parliament.\n\n===2014 European Parliament elections===\n[[File:Bernd Lucke 05.JPG|right|thumb|[[Bernd Lucke]], former leader of Alternative for Germany]]\nThe [[2014 European Parliament election|2014 European elections]] were held on 22\u201325 May 2014. On 4 June 2014, the ECR accepted applications from the [[Danish People's Party]] (4 MEPs) and the [[Finns Party]] (2 MEPs), both formerly attached to the EFD group during the 7th term of the European Parliament, as well as the [[Family Party of Germany]], both [[Ordinary People (Slovakia)|Ordinary People and Independent Personalities]] (O\u013daNO) and [[New Majority (Slovakia)|New Majority]] (NOVA) from Slovakia, and the [[Independent Greeks]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Barker|first1=Alex|title=MEPs with criminal records join Tories' eurosceptic group|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d0b45ce0-ec11-11e3-a9e3-00144feabdc0.html|accessdate=4 June 2014|work=Financial Times|date=4 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Cerulus|first1=Laurens|title=Cameron's group challenges liberals as kingmakers in new Parliament|url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/eu-elections-2014/camerons-group-challenges-liberals-kingmakers-new-parliament-302631|accessdate=5 June 2014|publisher=EurActive|date=5 June 2014}}</ref> [[Alternative for Germany]] and [[Bulgaria Without Censorship]] were admitted on 8 June, followed by the Dutch [[Reformed Political Party]] on 16 June.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.sgp.nl/Actueel/Belder%20in%20ECR.wli|title= Belder in ECR|date= 16 June 2014|accessdate= 16 June 2014}}</ref> On 18 June the [[New Flemish Alliance]] (N-VA) joined the group,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.standaard.be/cnt/dmf20140618_01146790|title=N-VA kiest voor ECR-fractie in Europees Parlement |first= Johan|last= Van Overtveldt|date= 18 June 2014|work= standaard.be|language= Dutch|trans-title=N-VA chooses ECR Group in the European Parliament|accessdate= 18 June 2014}}</ref> a party previously attached to the [[Greens/EFA]] group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/eu-elections-2014/dispute-flemish-meps-shows-crack-news-530679 |title=Flemish MEP row reveals tensions in Greens/EFA group |publisher=EurActiv.com |date=25 May 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> N-VA party members had voted by a wide margin to join the ECR group instead of ALDE; 70 voted to join the ECR, and just three to join ALDE.<ref name=\"euractiv.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/eu-elections-2014/liberals-embarrassed-n-va-joins-ecr-making-it-third-largest-parliament |title=Liberals embarrassed as N-VA joins ECR, making it third largest Parliament group |publisher=EurActiv.com |date=19 June 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> The N-VA's decision allowed the ECR to overtake ALDE as the third biggest group in the European parliament,<ref name=\"euractiv.com\"/> assuming the role of \"kingmakers\" in the new parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/eu-elections-2014/camerons-group-challenges-liberals-kingmakers-new-parliament-302631 |title=Cameron's group challenges liberals as kingmakers in new Parliament |publisher=EurActiv.com |date= 5 June 2014|accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref> On 23 June, Irish [[Fianna F\u00e1il]] MEP [[Brian Crowley]] joined from the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Group|ALDE]] group, but without the permission of his party or its leader [[Miche\u00e1l Martin]], who removed Crowley's party whip the following day.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bardon |first=Sarah |url=http://www.irishmirror.ie/news/irish-news/politics/fianna-fail-expel-mep-brian-3752690 |title=Fianna Fail expel MEP Brian Crowley \u2013 Irish Mirror Online |publisher=Irishmirror.ie |date=24 June 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2014/0624/626038-fianna-fail/|title=Brian Crowley loses Fianna F\u00e1il whip|publisher=[[RT\u00c9 News]]|date=24 June 2014}}</ref> On the same day, [[IMRO \u2013 Bulgarian National Movement]] joined,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/EuropeDecides/status/481460090902687744 |title=Europe Decides on Twitter: \"ALDE and ECR both gained new members today: Angel Dzhambazki from BG joined @ecrgroup Mircea Diaconu from RO joined @ALDEgroup #EP2014\" |publisher=Twitter |date=24 June 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2015}}{{Primary source inline|date=January 2020}}</ref> taking the group to 70 MEPs.\n\nThe ECR's unanimous decision to admit the Danish People's Party and Finns Party as members was criticised because one MEP from each party has a criminal conviction.<ref>''Private Eye'', Issue 1369, 27 June \u2013 10 July 2014, pg. 16.</ref><ref>Watt, Nicholas (June 2014) [https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/jun/05/david-cameron-under-fire-as-dpp-and-true-finns-enter-ecr-group \u201cDavid Cameron accused over 'dubious' European Union partners\u201d] ''The Guardian'', Thursday 5 June 2014 Accessed 25 June 2014.</ref> [[Morten Messerschmidt]], lead candidate for the Danish People's Party, was convicted in 2002 for publishing material that appeared to suggest that there is a link between a multiethnic society and rape, violence and forced marriages.<ref name=\"ft.com\">Barker, Alex (June 2014). [http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d0b45ce0-ec11-11e3-a9e3-00144feabdc0.html \u201cMEPs with criminal records join Tories\u2019 eurosceptic group\u201d] ''Financial Times'', 4 June 2014 Accessed 25 June 2014.</ref> [[Jussi Halla-aho]], a Finns Party MEP, was convicted in 2012 after writing a 2008 blog entry which claimed that Islam \"reveres paedophilia\".<ref name=\"ft.com\"/> However, [[Syed Kamall]], the ECR's chairman, who is a practising Muslim, defended the new members.<ref name=\"ft.com\"/>\n\nFollowing the election, British Conservative MEP [[Sajjad Karim]] was the group's candidate for [[President of the European Parliament]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sajjadkarim.eu/2014/06/15/sajjads-european-parliament-presidential-campaign-heats-up/ |title=Sajjad's European Parliament Presidential campaign heats up |publisher=Sajjadkarim.eu |date=15 June 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140617143342/http://www.sajjadkarim.eu/2014/06/15/sajjads-european-parliament-presidential-campaign-heats-up/ |archivedate=17 June 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2016, the bureau of the ECR Group began motions to exclude the two remaining MEPs of the [[Alternative for Germany]] (AfD) from their group due to the AfD's links with the far-right [[Freedom Party of Austria]] (FP\u00d6) and controversial remarks about immigration, inviting the MEPs to voluntarily leave the group by 31 March, with a motion of exclusion to be tabled on 12 April otherwise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euractiv.com/section/social-europe-jobs/news/afd-links-to-austrian-far-right-final-straw-for-ecr-meps/|title=AfD links to Austrian far-right 'final straw' for ECR MEPs|date=9 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://euobserver.com/political/132619|title=EU parliament group tells German AfD party to leave}}</ref>\n\n===Changes in membership 2014\u20132019===\n*On 2 October 2014, the leader of the Slovak party [[Freedom and Solidarity]] (SaS), [[Richard Sulik]], left the ALDE group to join the ECR,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.aecr.eu/sas-leader-richard-sulik-leaves-alde-and-applies-to-join-ecr/ |title=SaS leader Richard Sul\u00edk leaves ALDE and applies to join ECR &#124; AECR |publisher=Aecr.eu |date=2 October 2014 |accessdate=14 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117023407/http://www.aecr.eu/sas-leader-richard-sulik-leaves-alde-and-applies-to-join-ecr/ |archive-date=17 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and was formally accepted six days later.\n*In November 2014, the sole Croatian member of the group, [[Ru\u017ea Toma\u0161i\u0107]], left the party she founded, [[Croatian Party of Rights dr. Ante Star\u010devi\u0107]], to lead a new party, the [[Croatian Conservative Party]].\n*On 24 January 2015, [[Amjad Bashir]], the [[UKIP]] MEP for [[Yorkshire and the Humber (European Parliament constituency)|Yorkshire and the Humber]], changed affiliation to the Conservative Party and subsequently joined the ECR.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-30967633|title=UKIP MEP Amjad Bashir defects to Conservative Party |publisher=BBC News|accessdate=10 February 2016|date=24 January 2015}}</ref>\n*On 18 May 2015, [[Raffaele Fitto]], formerly of Italian party [[Forza Italia (2013)|Forza Italia]] and EPP group member, joined the ECR group: forming a party called the [[Conservatives and Reformists (Italy)|Conservatives and Reformists]] after the ECR.<ref name=\"ilvelino\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ilvelino.it/it/article/2015/05/19/parlamento-ue-fitto-e-entrato-nel-gruppo-ecr/d630b0cf-3e54-4cf5-9588-eaed064f5aee/|title=Parlamento Ue, Fitto &#232; entrato nel gruppo Ecr (19 mag 2015) \u2013 ilVelino/AGV NEWS|publisher=ilvelino.it|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"theparliamentmagazine\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/movers-and-shakers-may-2015|title=Movers and Shakers &#124; The Parliament Magazine|publisher=theparliamentmagazine.eu|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n*On 7 July 2015, [[Remo Sernagiotto]] left the EPP to join the ECR.\n*On 27 October 2015, [[Monica Macovei]], from [[M10 (political party)|M10 political party]] left the EPP to join the ECR.<ref name=\"agerpres\">{{cite web|url=http://www.agerpres.ro/comunicate/2015/10/27/comunicat-de-presa-europarlamentar-monica-macovei-19-41-12|title=Comunicat de pres\u0103 \u2013 Europarlamentar Monica Macovei |publisher=agerpres.ro|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n*On 8 March 2016, [[Eleni Theocharous]] of the Cypriot [[Democratic Rally]] was admitted to the group from the EPP.<ref>{{cite news|title=ECR group welcomes Eleni Theocharous|url=http://ecrgroup.eu/news/ecr-group-welcomes-eleni-theocharous/|accessdate=9 March 2016|publisher=European Conservatives and Reformists group|date=9 March 2016}}</ref>\n*On 5 October 2016, [[Timothy Kirkhope]] was forced to quit after being created a [[life peer]] in the UK [[House of Lords]], and thus becoming ineligible to continue serving in the [[European Parliament]]. His seat was succeeded by John Procter.\n*On 3 July 2018, [[Peter Lundgren (politician)|Peter Lundgren]] and [[Kristina Winberg]], from [[Sweden Democrats]] left EFDD group to join ECR group.<ref>{{cite news|title=ECR group approves two new members, Peter Lundgren and Kristina Winberg|url=http://ecrgroup.eu/ecr-group-approves-two-new-members-peter-lundgren-and-kristina-winberg/|accessdate=8 July 2018|publisher=European Conservatives and Reformists group|date=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n*On 17 December 2018, [[Stefano Maullu]] left the EPP group to join the ECR group after his defection from [[Forza Italia (2013)|Forza Italia]] to the [[Brothers of Italy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/movers-and-shakers-17-december-2018|title=Movers and Shakers \u2013 17 December 2018|website=theparliamentmagazine.eu}}</ref>\n\n===2019 European Parliament elections===\nPrior to the 2019 elections, the [[Sweden Democrats]] and [[Brothers of Italy]] joined the ECR group,<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Financial Times]]|date=28 November 2018|title=Tory Eurosceptic alliance looks to Salvini after Brexit|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9445faec-f397-11e8-9623-d7f9881e729f}}</ref> while [[Forum for Democracy (Netherlands)|Forum for Democracy]] and [[Debout la France]] have pledged to do so after the elections should they win seats during them.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theparliamentmagazine.eu/articles/news/party-leaders-join-ecr-group-after-eu-elections|title=Party leaders to join ECR group after EU elections|website=theparliamentmagazine.eu}}</ref>\n\nTwo ECR member parties, the [[Danish People's Party]] and the [[Finns Party]], announced their intention to form a new group called the [[European Alliance for People and Nations]] with [[Alternative for Germany]] and Italy's [[Lega Nord|League]] following the 2019 elections.<ref>{{cite news|work=[[Saudi Gazette]]|title=EU's nationalist parties announce plans to join forces after May vote|date=8 April 2019|url=http://saudigazette.com.sa/article/562988/World/Europe/EUs-nationalist-parties-announce-plans-to-join-forces-after-May-vote}}</ref>\n\nThe Dutch [[Christian Union (Netherlands)|Christian Union]] (CU) switched to the [[European People's Party group]] after the election with the CU's sole MEP [[Peter van Dalen]] arguing that the ECR was moving too far to the right with the inclusion of the [[Forum for Democracy (Netherlands)|Forum for Democracy]] and the [[Sweden Democrats]].<ref>{{cite news|work=Teller Report|title=ChristenUnie does not want Forum for Democracy: A European family quarrel|date=22 April 2019|url=https://www.tellerreport.com/news/2019-05-22---christenunie-does-not-want-forum-for-democracy--a-european-family-quarrel-.SJbMgUZmpE.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Conservatives and Reformists Summit ===\n* 2015 Conservatives and Reformists Summit: [[Tunis]] ([[Tunisia]])<ref>[http://www.aecr.eu/conservatives-and-reformists-summit/ AECR President Jan Zahradil opens Tunis Summit] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415090606/http://www.aecr.eu/conservatives-and-reformists-summit/ |date=15 April 2016 }}, AECR News, 13 November 2015</ref>\n* 2016 Conservatives and Reformists Summit: [[Antalya]] ([[Turkey]])<ref>[http://www.changeandwin.org Conservatives and Reformists Summit Antalya], AECR News, changeandwin.org, March 2016</ref>\n\n==Membership==\n{{Main|List of European Conservatives and Reformists Members of the European Parliament}}\n=== Ninth European Parliament ===\nFollowing the [[2019 European Parliament election|2019 election]], the ECR got 61 seats. The [[Finns Party]] and the [[Danish People's Party]] agreed to leave the group and join [[Identity and Democracy]] after the election. After those losses, four parties joined the group: the Spanish [[Vox (political party)|Vox]], the [[Family Party of Germany]], [[Greek Solution]] and the Dutch [[Forum for Democracy]].\n\nECR currently has 61 [[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]] from 15 countries.\n\n===Eighth European Parliament===\nFollowing the 2014 election, members from twelve new parties joined. Additional parties were admitted during the course of the [[Eighth European Parliament]], such as the Slovak [[Freedom and Solidarity]] party and the Italian [[Conservatives and Reformists (Italy)|Direzione Italia]]. [[Alternative for Germany]] was initially admitted, but expelled in April 2016.\n\nIn 2019 the ECR had 77 [[Member of the European Parliament|Members of the European Parliament]],<ref>{{cite web |title=2014\u20132019 Outgoing Parliament |url=https://www.election-results.eu/european-results/2014-2019/outgoing-parliament/ |website=European Parliament |accessdate=20 July 2019 }}</ref> from twenty-three parties across eighteen countries. The ECR drew the majority of its MEPs from [[northern Europe|northern]] and central Europe.\n\n===Seventh European Parliament===\nOriginally, it had been announced on 22 June 2009 that [[Hannu Takkula]], MEP for the Finnish [[Centre Party (Finland)|Centre Party]] (an [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] member party) would also be a member of ECR (with his two party colleagues remaining in ALDE), but he reversed this decision two days later.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newsroom.finland.fi/stt/showarticle.asp?intNWSAID=22191&group=Politics |title=NewsRoom Finland |publisher=Newsroom.finland.fi |accessdate=27 April 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe group membership was reduced to 54 when Edward McMillan-Scott was expelled from the group in July 2009. It increased to 55 again when [[Anna Rosbach]] joined the group in March 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rosbach leaves Danish People's Party to become ECR MEP |first=Martha |last=Moss |url=http://www.theparliament.com/latest-news/article/newsarticle/rosbach-leaves-danish-peoples-party-to-become-ecr-mep/ |newspaper=The Parliament |date=9 March 2011 |accessdate=10 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110313085011/http://www.theparliament.com/latest-news/article/newsarticle/rosbach-leaves-danish-peoples-party-to-become-ecr-mep |archivedate=13 March 2011 }}</ref> [[UKIP]] MEP [[David Campbell Bannerman]] rejoined the Conservative Party in May 2011, taking the group's tally to 56:<ref>{{cite news |title=David Campbell Bannerman returns to the Tories |first=Caroline |last=Crampton |url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/blog/159392/david-campbell-bannerman-returns-to-the-tories.thtml |newspaper=[[Total Politics]] |date=24 May 2011 |accessdate=24 May 2011}}</ref> one larger than [[The Greens\u2013European Free Alliance]] \u2013 an advantage that disappeared in June 2011. [[Anthea McIntyre]] was confirmed as the ECR's 57th MEP on 1 December 2011. [[United Poland]], which had been founded by four defectors from Law and Justice \u2013 [[Zbigniew Ziobro]], [[Tadeusz Cyma\u0144ski]], [[Jacek Kurski]], and {{Interlanguage link multi|Jacek W\u0142osowicz|pl}} \u2013 left the ECR for [[Europe of Freedom and Democracy]] (EFD) on 26 December 2011. In March 2012, Conservative [[Roger Helmer]] defected to the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP) and also joined EFD; [[Marta Andreasen]] moved in the opposite direction, joining the Conservatives and the ECR from UKIP and the EFD group, in February 2013.{{citation needed|date=January 2015}}  In October 2012, [[Cristiana Muscardini]] joined the ECR, when she left [[Future and Freedom]] to found the [[Conservatives and Social Reformers]]. In April 2013, the ECR was joined by fellow Italian [[Susy De Martini]], an independent who was formerly a member of [[The People of Freedom]]. The [[2013 European Parliament election in Croatia|newly elected]] Croatian MEP [[Ru\u017ea Toma\u0161i\u0107]] of the [[Croatian Party of Rights dr. Ante Star\u010devi\u0107|Croatian Party of Rights]] joined the group when Croatia joined the EU in July 2013.<ref name=\"Ruza Tomasic joins\">{{cite news |title=Ruza Tomasic joins the group of European Conservatives in EU parliament |url=http://www.croatiantimes.com/news/General_News/2013-06-10/33814/Ruza_Tomasic_joins_the_group_of_European_Conservatives_in_EU_parliament |newspaper=Croatian Times |date=10 June 2013 |accessdate=14 June 2013 }}</ref> In November 2013, [[Poland Comes First]] dissolved itself, with three of its members joining the new [[Poland Together]], which was also joined by [[Artur Zasada]] from the EPP: taking the group's number of MEPs to 57. In 2014, [[Miros\u0142aw Piotrowski]] rejoined [[Law and Justice]], and sought re-election in 2014 under that party's banner.\n\n==MEPs==\n\n=== 9th European Parliament ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%\