ta/color}}\" |\n|Independent\n|{{Composition bar 2|4|51|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2014|July|1}}\n|-\n|{{ROM}}\n|[[M10 (political party)|M<sup>10</sup>]]\n|style=\"background:{{Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe|ACRE]]\n|{{Composition bar 2|1|32|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2015|October|27}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | {{flag|Slovakia}}\n| [[Freedom and Solidarity]]<br>''Sloboda a Solidarita'' ''(SaS)''\n|style=\"background:{{Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe|ACRE]]\n| {{Composition bar 2|1|13|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2014|October|8}}\n|-\n|[[New Majority (Slovakia)|New Majority]]<br>''NOVA''\n|style=\"background:{{Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe|ACRE]]\n|{{Composition bar 2|1|13|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2014|June|4}}\n|-\n|[[Ordinary People (Slovakia)|Ordinary People]]<br>''Oby\u010dajn\u00ed \u013dudia a nez\u00e1visl\u00e9 osobnosti (O\u013daNO)''\n|style=\"background:{{European Christian Political Movement/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[European Christian Political Movement|ECPM]]\n|{{Composition bar 2|1|13|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2014|June|4}}\n|-\n| {{flag|Sweden}}\n|[[Sweden Democrats]]<br>''Sverigedemokraterna'' ''(SD)''\n|style=\"background:{{Non-Inscrits/meta/color}}\" |\n|''None''\n| {{Composition bar 2|2|20|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2018|July|3}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | {{flag|United Kingdom}}\n|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]<br>''Conservative and Unionist Party'' ''(Con)''\n| style=\"background:{{Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe|ACRE]]\n| {{Composition bar 2|8<ref>https://www.express.co.uk/news/uk/1225490/Brexit-news-Annunziata-Rees-Mogg-Lance-Forman-John-Longworth-Lucy-Harris-Conservative</ref>|73|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2009|June|22}}\n|-\n|[[Ulster Unionist Party]]<br>''(UUP)''\n| style=\"background:{{Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe/meta/color}}\" |\n|[[Alliance of Conservatives and Reformists in Europe|ACRE]]\n|{{Composition bar 2|1|73|hex={{European Conservatives and Reformists/meta/color}}}}\n|{{dts|format=dmy|2009|June|22}}\n|-\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n{{reflist |group=note}}\n\n\n==Leadership==\n\n===Chairman===\nThe ECR currently is led by a two Co-Chairmen, [[Ryszard Legutko]] of the Polish [[Law and Justice]] party and [[Raffaele Fitto]] of the [[Brothers of Italy]] party.\n\nThere have been five Chairmen of the European Conservatives and Reformists group:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Assumed office\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| To\n! style=\"width:150px;\"|  Name\n! style=\"width:300px;\"|  Party\n|-\n| 24 June 2009\n| 14 July 2009\n| [[Timothy Kirkhope]]\n| {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n|-\n| 14 July 2009\n| 8 March 2011\n| [[Micha\u0142 Kami\u0144ski]]\n| {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Law and Justice]] / [[Poland Comes First]]\n|-\n| 8 March 2011\n| 14 December 2011\n| [[Jan Zahradil]]\n| {{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[Civic Democratic Party (Czech Republic)|Civic Democratic Party]]\n|-\n| 14 December 2011\n| 12 June 2014\n| [[Martin Callanan]]\n| {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n|-\n| 12 June 2014\n| 2019\n| [[Syed Kamall]]\n| {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n|}\n\n===Group Bureau===\n{{Main|European Conservatives and Reformists Group Executive}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Position\n! style=\"width:150px;\"| Name\n! style=\"width:300px;\"| Party\n|-\n| Co-Chairman\n| [[Ryszard Legutko]]\n| {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Law and Justice]]\n|-\n| Co-Chairman\n| [[Raffaele Fitto]]\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Brothers of Italy]]\n|-\n| {{nowrap|Vice-Chairman}}\n| [[Roberts Z\u012ble]]\n| {{flagicon|Latvia}} [[National Alliance (Latvia)|National Alliance]]\n|-\n| Vice-Chairman\n| [[Assita Kanko]]\n| {{flagicon|Belgium}} [[New Flemish Alliance]]\n|-\n| Vice-Chairman\n| [[Peter Lundgren]]\n| {{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Swedish Democrats]]\n|-\n| Vice-Chairman\n| [[Derk Jan Eppink]]\n| {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Forum for Democracy]]\n|-\n| Vice-Chairman\n| [[Hermann Tertsch]]\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Vox (political party)|Vox]]\n|-\n| Co-Treasurer\n| [[Kosma Z\u0142otowski]]\n| {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Law and Justice]]\n|-\n| Co-Treasurer\n| [[Angel Dzhambazki]]\n| {{flagicon|Bulgaria}} [[IMRO \u2013 Bulgarian National Movement]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== Cohesion ==\nAccording to calculations by ''Vote Watch Europe'', the ECR group had a cohesion rate of 86.65% in parliamentary votes during the 7th session (2009\u201314). This is slightly lower than in the four pro-European groups, but higher than in the [[European United Left\u2013Nordic Green Left]] (GUE/NGL) and far higher than in the [[Europe of Freedom and Democracy]] (EFD) groups. Internal cohesion was highest in votes on constitutional and inter-institutional affairs (94.79%), international trade, and industry, research & energy. The greatest divergence within the group was in decisions on regional development (70.53% cohesion), agriculture, and development (cooperation).<ref>{{Citation |url=http://term7.votewatch.eu/en/political-group-cohesion.html |title=Cohesion of (trans-national) political groups in the European Parliament |publisher=Vote Watch Europe |accessdate=2 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140713035533/http://term7.votewatch.eu/en/political-group-cohesion.html |archivedate=13 July 2014 }}</ref> The parties that were most loyal to the group (meaning that they voted with the majority of ECR members the most often) were the UK Conservatives (97.51%), the Ulster Unionist Party and the Czech Civic Democratic Party. The members who deviated from the ECR majority the most often were the individual MEPs Andreasen from the UK (who had switched over from EFD group only in 2013; 61.20% loyalty), Muscardini from Italy, and Rosbach (who had crossed over from EFD in 2011).<ref>{{Citation |url=http://term7.votewatch.eu/en/national-parties-loyalties.html#/#0/0/2009-07-14/2014-07-14/9/ |title=National party statistics \u2013 Voting loyalty to political group: ECR \u2013 European Conservatives and Reformists Group regarding All policy areas in the interval 2009-07-14 \u2013 2014-07-14 |publisher=Vote Watch Europe |accessdate=2 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140709040027/http://term7.votewatch.eu/en/national-parties-loyalties.html#/ |archive-date=9 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==See also ==\n* [[European Conservatives]], an earlier political group of Conservatives in the European Parliament\n* [[European Conservatives and Reformists Group Executive]]\n* [[Movement for European Reform]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.ecrgroup.eu/ European Conservatives and Reformists official website]\n* [http://www.europarl.europa.eu/members/expert/groupAndCountry/search.do?group=2977&language=EN Members of the group]\n* [http://conservativehome.blogs.com/thetorydiary/2009/06/the-deal-is-done-new-conservative-grouping-in-the-european-parliament-to-be-launched-today.html ConservativeHome (2009-06-22): The deal is done: Details of the new Conservative grouping in the European Parliament]\n\n{{EuroparlGroup}}\n{{Alliance of European Conservatives and Reformists}}\n{{Brexit note}}\n\n[[Category:E